Prepare ImageDataGenerator for data augmentation¶

Rotation- The images are rotated randomly from 0-20 degrees
Horizontal_flip- The images are flipped horizontally
Validation_split- Fraction of images reserved for validation

Plot Learning Curves¶

Plot accuracy on the training and validation datasets over training epochs.

Plot loss on the training and validation datasets over training epochs.

In [15]:
# function to plot the learning curves
def plot_results(history):
    
    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(20,7))

    ax1.plot(history['loss'], label="Train loss")
    ax1.plot(history['val_loss'], label="Validation loss")
    ax2.plot(history['accuracy'], label="Train accuracy")
    ax2.plot(history['val_accuracy'], label="Validation accuracy")

    ax1.legend(fontsize=15);
    ax2.legend(fontsize=15);

    ax1.set_title('Loss per epoch', fontsize=25);
    ax1.set_xlabel("epoch", fontsize=20);
    ax2.set_title('Accuracy per epoch', fontsize=25);
    ax2.set_xlabel("epoch", fontsize=20);

    ax1.grid(True)
    ax2.grid(True);

Early Stopping¶

Early Stopping is a callback that allows you to specify the performance measure to monitor, the trigger, and once triggered, it will stop the training process.

In [16]:
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping
#Setting early_stopping callback
early_stopping = EarlyStopping(
    monitor='val_accuracy',
    patience=15,
    min_delta=0.0000001,
    restore_best_weights=True,
)

Baseline Model¶

In [19]:
def get_model():
    
    #Input shape = [width, height, color channels]
    inputs = tf.keras.layers.Input(shape=(28, 28, 1))
    
    # Block One
    x = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(inputs)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D()(x)

    # Block Two
    x = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same')(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D()(x)

    # Head
    x = tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu')(x)
    
    #Final Layer (Output)
    output = tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')(x)
    
    model = tf.keras.Model(inputs=[inputs], outputs=output)
    
    return model_base

# defining the model
model_improved1 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    # Block One
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=3, input_shape=[28,28,1], activation='relu', padding="same"),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Block Two
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Block Three
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Head
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')
])

Model 2¶

In [35]:
# defining the CNN model
model_improved2 = tf.keras.Sequential([
    # Block One
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=3, input_shape=[28,28,1], activation='relu', padding="same"),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Block Two
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Block Three
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
    
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'),
    tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),

    # Head
    tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization(),
    tf.keras.layers.Flatten(),
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(64, activation='relu'),
    tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.3),
    
    tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')
])
model_improved2.summary()

Hyperparameter Search (Keras Tuner: Hyperband)¶

Tune the best model, which is improved model 2, with the higher validation accuracy and lower validation loss

-Parameters input dropout to between 0.1 and 0.2 because dropping the input data can adversely affect the training.
-Parameters intermediate dropout to 0.5 and below because 0.5 is not ideal for small datasets and >0.5 is not advised it may cull more connections without boosting the regularization.
In [32]:
def tune_model(hp):
    first_dropout=hp.Float('dropout',min_value=0.1, max_value=0.2, sampling="log")
    intermediate_dropout=hp.Float('dropout',min_value=0.1, max_value=0.5, sampling="log")
    dense_units=hp.Int('hl1-units', min_value=16, max_value=128, step=16)
    
    # Choose an optimal value from 0.1, 0.01, 0.001, or 0.0001
    learning_rate = hp.Choice('learning_rate', values=[1e-1, 1e-2, 1e-3, 1e-4])
    
    model = tf.keras.Sequential()
    # Block One
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=16, kernel_size=3, input_shape=[28,28,1], activation='relu', padding="same"))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=32, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(first_dropout))

    # Block Two
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=64, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(intermediate_dropout))

    # Block Three
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Conv2D(filters=128, kernel_size=3, activation='relu', padding='same'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.MaxPool2D())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(intermediate_dropout))

    # Head
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.BatchNormalization())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Flatten())
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(units=dense_units, activation='relu'))
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dropout(intermediate_dropout))
    
    model.add(tf.keras.layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax'))
    
    model.compile(loss='sparse_categorical_crossentropy',
                    optimizer=tf.keras.optimizers.Adam(learning_rate), metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

# To plot the visualisation of the predictions
def plot_image(i, predictions_array, true_label, img):
    predictions_array, true_label, img = predictions_array[i], true_label[i], img[i]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
  
    plt.imshow(img, cmap=plt.cm.binary)

    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)
    if predicted_label == true_label:
        color = 'blue'
    else:
        color = 'red'
  
    plt.xlabel("{} {:2.0f}% ({})".format(class_names[predicted_label],
                                100*np.max(predictions_array),
                                class_names[true_label]),
                                color=color)

def plot_value_array(i, predictions_array, true_label):
    predictions_array, true_label = predictions_array[i], true_label[i]
    plt.grid(False)
    plt.xticks([])
    plt.yticks([])
    thisplot = plt.bar(range(10), predictions_array, color="#777777")
    plt.ylim([0, 1]) 
    predicted_label = np.argmax(predictions_array)
 
    thisplot[predicted_label].set_color('red')
    thisplot[true_label].set_color('blue')
